What's your thought on finding passion?
text:
People always say, "Do something you love or feel enthusiastic about." I'm 20 years old and personally I don't feel anything like that. How does this "passion" work? How do you figure it out? Many people are working on what they love or feel genuine about. I feel envious towards them. For a while, I started feeling extreme depression, anxiety, and identity crisis. I don't know how to figure this out. I'm at a loss here and I feel extremely pathetic about this fact.
Can anybody find their passion? Is it possible that I'm not capable of figuring this out?

Show HN: A mix between Hacker News and Twitter
text:
Tech Noise - A social/news mobile app powered the tech community.

I just launched my startup ‘Tech Noise’. It’s a mix between Hacker News and Twitter.It has the minimal social/news aspect of hacker news with the subtle feel and design of Twitter along with its social features.

I would appreciate any feedback either good or bad, and especially bad. Likewise, you can submit feedback once you created an account and navigate to the settings screen by clicking on the settings bottom tab icon where you’ll see a button to submit feedback.

In addition, the app is available for download. Please keep in mind the app is open for testing to the public and I expect bugs lol. Once again, I would appreciate feedback :).

Remember, KEEP MOVING FORWARD, NEVER give up, and stay on your purpose and achieve your dreams and goals. YOU got this, keep the faith, and KEEP WORKING AND BELIEVING - dream, work, build, and create.

Peace and much love family!

Advice for someone considering becoming manager of developer experience team
text:
I've been an engineering manager for a product focused team for a little over a year now. Prior to that, I was a software engineer on a product team for a few years.

I was just asked if I'd like to switch to manage the developer experience team at my company as they sorely need a manager. That team handles things like staging environments, CI/CD pipelines, and general tooling that enables developers at our company to be productive.

I'm inclined to say yes because I feel this will be a good opportunity for growth for me as a manger, especially given that the work is in parts of our tech stack that I'm less familiar with.

However, I was wondering if anyone has any advice or wisdom to consider when making this choice. If you happen to manage a team like this, what has your experience been like? Do you know of any articles or blog posts that can shed some insight as to what it is like?

Thanks!
